INSERT INTO `solutions` VALUES (81,3331,'Hint','Multiplication of two cosines : \r\ncos(A)*cos(B) = 0.5[cos(A+B)+cos(A-B)]',0,0,0,1),(84,705,'Hint','Phasor Addition',0,0,0,1),(83,3331,'Det','x(t) = 10 + 8cos(40*pi*t-pi/3) + 12cos(100*pi*t+pi/4) +20cos(160*pi*t) <br><br>\r\ny(t) = x(t) cos(40*pi*t) <br><br>\r\n<b>Geometrical understanding :</b> <br>\r\nModulation property - When you multiply a signal with a property, the spectral line for each frequency moves up and down by the frequency of the modulating signal. Hence in this case, every spectral line will be moved up and down by 20 ( on frequency line) <br><br>\r\nFollowing that reshuffling, the -20 Hz component gets shifted to the right to reach DC and the 20 Hz component gets shifted to the left to reach DC. These are the two spectral lines at DC. <br>\r\nMathematically, we have to use the formula, cosA*cosB = 0.5[cos(A+B) + cos(A-B)]<br><br>\r\nSo, DC = 4cos(pi/3)',0,0,0,1),(87,3309,'Det','<latex>x(t) = 5 + 6cos(30\\pi*t-3*\\frac{pi}{4}) + 4cos(80\\pi*t-\\frac{pi}{3})</latex> <br><br>\r\n\r\n<latex>y(t) = x(t)cos(30\\pi*t) </latex><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Geometrical understanding :</b> <br>\r\nModulation property - When you multiply a signal with a property, the spectral line for each frequency moves up and down by the frequency of the modulating signal. Hence in this case, every spectral line will be moved up and down by 30. <br><br>\r\n\r\nFollowing that reshuffling, the -30 component gets shifted to the right to reach DC and the 30 Hz component gets shifted to the left to reach DC. These are the two spectral lines at DC. <br><br>\r\n\r\nMathematically, we have to use the formula, <latex>cos(A)*cos(B) = 0.5[cos(A+B) + cos(A-B)] </latex><br><br>\r\n\r\nSo, <latex>DC = 3*cos(3*\\frac{\\pi}{4})</latex>\r\n',0,0,0,1),(86,3309,'Hint','cosA*cosB = 0.5[cos(A+B) + cos(A-B)]',0,0,0,1),(14,3481,'Sol','<latex> (2+ cos(2 pi 10 t))^{2} = 4 + cos^{2}(2 pi 10 t) + 2cos(2 pi 10 t) = 4 + frac{1}{2} + frac{1}{2}cos(4 pi 10 t)) + 2cos(2 pi 10 t) </latex>\r\n<br>Here, the DC term is the term that is independent of t, which is frac{9}{2}',0,0,1,1),(15,3484,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,0,1),(16,3484,'Sol','Test Solution',0,0,0,1),(17,3486,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,0,1),(18,3486,'Sol','Test Solution',0,0,0,1),(19,3489,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,0,1),(20,3489,'Sol','Test Solution',0,0,0,1),(21,3491,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,0,1),(22,3491,'Sol','Test Solution',0,0,0,1),(24,3471,'Sol','The impulse response of an FIR filter lasts for N+1 samples, and here, the filter order, i.e., N is 3.',0,0,1,1),(26,3472,'Sol','Here, N is 3 and the length of the filter is N+1, which is 4.',0,0,1,1),(28,3473,'Sol','At n = 1, the unit impulse function will have a nonzero value because a unit impulse function must have its parameter equal to zero in order to have a nonzero value.',0,0,1,1),(29,3479,'Hint','Test Hint',3,2.33,1,1),(30,3479,'Sol','Since the sum is from 0 to 1, there are two terms, each of which is multiplied with a constant, 2. Therefore, the answer is [2,2].',0,0,1,1),(31,3483,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,1,1),(32,3483,'Sol','Yes, the system is causal because each term in the impulse response is in the form <latex>delta</latex>[n - k], where k <latex> geq </latex> 0',0,0,1,1),(33,3487,'Hint','To check for aliasing or folding, compare the frequency of the sinusoid with the sampling frequency.',0,0,1,1),(34,3487,'Sol','The answer cannot be determined because there is insufficient information provided.',0,0,1,1),(35,3487,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,1,1),(36,3487,'Sol','Test Solution',0,0,1,1),(37,3488,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,1,1),(38,3488,'Sol','<latex>hat{omega} = 0.2 pi</latex>\r\n=> <latex> 2 pi frac{f}{fs} = 0.2 pi\r\n=> fs = 10f = 18000 Hz',0,0,1,1),(39,3478,'Hint','Test Hint',0,0,1,1),(40,3478,'Sol','Generally, continuous signals are denoted by using parentheses and discrete-time signals are denoted using square brackets. Therefore, the first option is correct.',0,0,1,1),(42,3474,'Sol','The z-transform of x[n-k] is <latex> z^{k} 